\details{
This function is value-agnostic: pass any long-format data frame with
\code{analyte} and \code{value} columns and it will compute one time-weighted value
per (focal_date × site_id × analyte).  Use it to aggregate raw chemistry
(\code{analyte} = chemical species, \code{summary = "geom_mean"}) or per-sample
AmsPAF values (\code{analyte = "AmsPAF"}, \code{summary = "arith_mean"}) into a
chronic predictor.

\strong{Forward-step duration weighting} treats each sample as representing the
period from its collection date to the next sample's date (or to
\code{focal_date} for the most recent sample).  This corrects for pulse-biased
sampling where storm events are sampled more frequently than base-flow
periods, which would otherwise over-weight episodic concentrations.

\strong{Exponential-decay temporal weighting} assigns higher weight to recent
samples, with a half-life of approximately \code{tau_days * log(2)} days.

These two components are the only weighting scheme offered, by design:
forward-step duration weighting is the minimal correction for irregular /
pulse-biased sampling, and exponential decay is the standard memory kernel
for a community integrating a fluctuating exposure (one interpretable
parameter, \code{tau_days}, tied to the target biology's response time).  Richer
kernels would add parameters without a defensible way to fit them from
routine monitoring data, so they are left out — tune \code{tau_days} rather than
swapping the kernel.

\strong{Combined weight} for sample \emph{i} is
\verb{w_i = Δt_i × exp(-(focal_date - midpoint_i) / tau_days)}, where
\code{midpoint_i} is the midpoint of sample \emph{i}'s representative interval.

\strong{Choosing \code{summary}:}
\itemize{
\item \code{"geom_mean"}: max-likelihood central tendency for log-normal data.
Use for chemistry concentrations.  Caveat: with highly pulsed exposure
and a non-linear SSD response, this underestimates the time-averaged
risk metric (Jensen's inequality on the upper tail of the SSD).
\item \code{"arith_mean"}: weighted arithmetic mean.  Use for bounded indices
like AmsPAF percentages, or for chemistry when comparison against an
arithmetic-mean compliance trigger is wanted.
\item \code{"p90"}: 90th percentile (duration-weighted empirical CDF).  Diagnostic
for "what's the upper-end exposure the community sees most of the
time."
}

For chronic AmsPAF specifically, the recommended pipeline is
\code{add_amspaf()} on per-sample chemistry, then \code{time_weighted_aggregate()}
